This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Dominick Maurice Velazquez in court, in custody.  Attorney Mary Garvin Guimont in court for Dominick Maurice Velazquez.  Prosecuting attorney Navjot Singh Hira in court for the State of Wisconsin. Deputy court clerk cmt. 
Case in court for return on doctors report.  Parties review and do not contest report. Court finds the defendant lacks substantial capacity to understand court proceedings or to assist in his own defense. Court orders proceedings suspended. Court ordered defendant committed to the Department of Health and Family Services for Institutional Care in order to restore competency within the statutory time frame with credit for 30 days time served. Defendant is REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department for transportation to the designated facility.  On defense motion, Court makes forthwith order. Order of Commitment signed and filed. Case adjourned, Branch 15.
